Gerald,<br><br>
Good to have you back.<br><br>
Three years ago I was bicycle riding in Germany and Austria. <br>
In a small Austrian resort town called Zell Am See, my wife and I accidentally rode through a zone where bikes weren't allowed - only foot traffic. A lady yelled at us, &quot;Verboten&quot;. I turned to my wife and said how our trip was now complete because a German told us something was, &quot;Verboten&quot;. She and I got a good laugh out of that.<br><br>
We also got a good laugh when Cook said that I have &quot;communist propaganda&quot; on my website - which is an INFORMATION site. We absolutely broke up into stitches when Cook referred to me as a &quot;compatriot&quot; of doc spatz. It would have been much less of an innuendo if he would have said that I was the &quot;little commie's&quot; &quot;comrade&quot;.<br><br>
Yep, back in the 50's Joe McCarthy liked to intimidate people. Back then, it worked. Some still even quote McCarthy, if you can believe that! Only thing is, that this type of ploy is so old that it has grown a beard.<br><br>
Sorry, can't help but laugh about it.<br><br>

